{{Infobox musical artist |name = Lydia Ainsworth |image = |caption = |background = group_or_band |origin = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada |genre = [[Electronic music|Electronic]], [[Experimental music|Experimental]], [[Independent music|Indie]], [[Film Score]] |years_active = 2013-Present |label = [[Arbutus Records]] |website = {{URL|http://www.lydiaainsworth.com}} }}
'''Lydia Ainsworth''' is a composer, producer and singer based in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. On September 30, 2014 she released her debut album ''Right From Real'' on [[Arbutus Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/rising/9517-lydia-ainsworth|title=Somewhere between serenity and terror lies the work of Canadian pop experimentalist Lydia Ainsworth.|publisher=Pitchfork|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2014/05/01/discover-the-epic-orchestral-pop-of-lydia-ainsworth|title=Discover the Epic, Orchestral Pop of Lydia Ainsworth|publisher=Fader|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref>
== Biography == Originally from Toronto, Ainsworth was born to a singer-songwriter father and a [[set designer]] mother. She began learning cello at age 10 and attended the [[Etobicoke School of the Arts]] as a teenager. She completed a [[Bachelor's degree]] in music composition at [[McGill University]] and was named an Emerging Artist by the [[Canada Council for the Arts]] in 2008. She moved to [[New York City]] to complete a [[Master's degree]] in music composition on a grant at [[New York University]]. She began composing student films while at McGill University, and in 2011 she composed the score for the film ''[[The Woods (2011 film)|The Woods]]'' directed by [[Matthew Lessner]]. She began recording her first album, ''Right from Real'', in her New York apartment after a period of self-imposed isolation, but completed the album in Toronto. The album was released by Montreal-based independent label Arbutus Records and in 2015 was a nominee for the [[Juno Award]] for the [[Juno Award for Electronic Album of the Year|Electronic Album of the Year]]. In 2016, she was named by [[CBC Music]] as one of "6 Canadian female producers you need to know." Ainsworth announced her second album, ''Darling of the Afterglow'', on January 10, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/20073/1/stream-the-magical-debut-ep-from-lydia-ainsworth|title=Stream the magical debut EP from Lydia Ainsworth|publisher=Dazed Digital|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/features/lydia-ainsworth_2/|title=T.O. native's debut weaves together classical and electronic|publisher=TorontoNow|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ascap.com/eventsawards/events/sundance/2011/bios/lydia-ainsworth|title=Lydia Ainsworth|publisher=ASCAP|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://grey-magazine.com/music-lydia-ainsworth|title=MUSIC: LYDIA AINSWORTH|publisher=Grey Magazine|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbcmusic.ca/posts/12516/six-canadian-women-producers-to-put-on-your-radar|title=6 Canadian female producers you need to know|publisher=CBC Music|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/Music/article/2015_juno_nominees_announced|title=2015 Juno nominees announced|publisher=Exclaim!|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/02/07/lydia-ainsworth-afterglow-music-video-premiere|title=Lydia Ainsworth Bathes In The "Afterglow" Of Her Mystical New Video|publisher=Fader|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref>
