{{Infobox person | name = Martha Byrne | image = ATWTafscheid4.jpg | caption = Byrne in 2012 | birth_name = Mary Martha Byrne | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1969|12|23}} | birth_place = [[Ridgewood, New Jersey]], U.S. | years_active = 1982–present | website = {{url|http://marthabyrne.net}} | occupation = Actress, singer, television writer | spouse = {{marriage|Michael McMahon|1994}} | children = 3 }}
'''Mary Martha Byrne'''<ref name=filmref /> (born December 23, 1969)<ref name=filmref>{{cite web|url= http://www.filmreference.com/film/47/Martha-Byrne.html|title=Martha Byrne Biography (1969-)|publisher= FilmReference.com |accessdate=February 26, 2018|archivedate=July 1, 2017|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170701081952/http://www.filmreference.com/film/47/Martha-Byrne.html|deadurl=no}}</ref> is an American actress, singer and television writer. She played the role of [[Lily Walsh|Lily Walsh Snyder]] on the [[soap opera]] ''[[As the World Turns]]'' from 1985 to 1989, then again from 1993 to 2008; as well as, from 2000 to 2003, Lily's twin sister, Rose D'Angelo. Byrne has also appeared in other stage, television and movie roles, including the title role in the 1983 film ''[[Anna to the Infinite Power]]''. She is currently executive producer of the digital drama series ''[[Anacostia (web series)|Anacostia]]'', where she has played the role of Alexis Jordan since 2011. Byrne has won three [[Daytime Emmy Award]]s for acting.
==Early life== Byrne was born in [[Ridgewood, New Jersey]], the daughter of Terrence Joseph and Mary Adele (née TuMulty) Byrne.<ref name=filmref />
==Career==
===Featured roles=== Byrne began acting at a young age when she joined the cast of the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] [[musical theatre|musical]] ''[[Annie (musical)|Annie]]'', where she played the role of July.
She was a featured actor on a number of prime time episodic television programs, including ''[[Kate and Allie]]'', ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]'', ''[[Parker Lewis Can't Lose]]'', ''[[Jake and the Fatman]]'', ''[[In the Heat of the Night (TV series)|In the Heat of the Night]]'', and ''[[Hearts are Wild]]''. Byrne also appeared in several television movies, with featured roles in ''When the Cradle Falls'' and ''[[Pink Lightning]].''
Byrne's best known film role was as the title character in the 1983 film ''[[Anna to the Infinite Power]]''. In 2010 she provided the commentary for the film's DVD release.
===Daytime television=== Byrne is best known for portraying [[Lily Walsh|Lily Walsh Snyder]] on the [[CBS Daytime]] [[soap opera]] ''[[As the World Turns]]''. She started in May 1985 at age 15, taking over from another teenage actress. Byrne soon became part of a "[[supercouple]]" when then-[[head writer]] [[Douglas Marland]] paired "poor little rich girl" Lily with hard-luck farmhand [[Holden Snyder]], played by [[Jon Hensley]]. The show attracted controversy in 1987 when Byrne—months shy of her 18th birthday—and equally underage actor [[Brian Bloom]] played out a storyline in which they lost their virginity to each other.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}<!-- Source needed to establish that this was actually controversial in the press. -->
Byrne won a [[Daytime Emmy Award]] for [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Younger Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Younger Actress]] in 1987. She left ''As the World Turns'' in 1989, and returned in April 1993. From 2000 until 2003, Byrne also played a second role, Lily's long-lost twin, Rose D'Angelo. She won another Daytime Emmy in 2001, this time as [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actress]].
Byrne left ''As the World Turns'' again in April 2008. The show's [[executive producer]] [[Christopher Goutman]] stated, "We made Martha an incredibly generous offer in hopes that she would remain a valuable member of the ''ATWT'' cast. Unfortunately, Martha has decided to leave despite our best efforts to keep her."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://community.tvguide.com/blog-entry/TVGuide-Editors-Blog/Soaps-News/Martha-Byrne-Exits/800034612 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080426234352/http://community.tvguide.com/blog-entry/TVGuide-Editors-Blog/Soaps-News/Martha-Byrne-Exits/800034612 |date=February 29, 2008 |archivedate=April 26, 2008 |accessdate=September 29, 2015 |work=[[TV Guide]] |first=Michael |last=Logan |authorlink=Michael Logan (journalist) |title=Martha Byrne Exits ''As the World Turns''}}</ref> Byrne later asserted that the contract negotiations fell through because the show refused to guarantee her the same number of episodes of work she had previously been guaranteed. She added that a casting call was made for her successor during her contract negotiations, which fueled her drive to leave.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}<!-- These comments attributed to Byrne require sourcing. --> Byrne's last airdate on the show was April 22, 2008; her successor, [[Noelle Beck]], appeared in the role of Lily from May 2008 until the series' end in 2010.
Byrne was hired as a script writer by [[Bradley Bell]] for ''[[The Bold and the Beautiful]]'' in early 2009. From June 17 though September 9, 2009, she portrayed [[Andrea Floyd]] on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] soap opera ''[[General Hospital]]''.
Byrne began portraying Alexis Jordan (née Joanne Edwards) on the soap opera [[web series]] ''[[Anacostia (web series)|Anacostia]]'' in 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soapoperadigest.com/content/exclusive-elizabeth-hubbard-joins-anacostia |title=Exclusive! Elizabeth Hubbard Joins ''Anacostia'' |work=[[Soap Opera Digest]] |date=September 17, 2015 |accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref> winning a 2012 [[Indie Series Award]] for [[3rd Indie Soap Awards|Best Guest Appearance (Drama)]],<ref name="Indie Win">{{cite web |url=http://www.indieseriesawards.com/2012/11/indie-soap-awards-history-and-archive.html |title=Indie Series Awards History and Archive of Past Winners |publisher=Indie Series Awards |accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref> and a 2015 [[Daytime Emmy Award]] for [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Performer in a New Approaches Drama Series|Outstanding Performer in a New Approaches Drama Series]].<ref name="Variety Emmy 42 Win">{{cite web|title=CBS, PBS and ''The Bold and the Beautiful'' Lead Daytime Creative Arts Emmy Winners |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/daytime-emmy-awards-bold-and-the-beautiful-cbs-alex-trebek-florence-henderson-1201479958/ |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=September 26, 2015| date=April 25, 2015}}</ref> The entire cast won a 2015 Indie Series Award for [[6th Indie Series Awards|Best Ensemble (Drama)]].<ref name="Indie Win"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indieseriesawards.com/2015/04/6th-Annual-Indie-Series-Awards-Winners.html |title=6th Annual Indie Series Awards: Complete List of Winners |publisher=[[Indie Series Awards]] |date=April 2015 |accessdate=September 17, 2015}}</ref> Byrne served as a co-executive producer, director and writer for the series from 2012-2016, and was promoted to Executive Producer in the show's 2017 fifth season. As a producer, Byrne was also nominated for the Daytime Emmy for [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding New Approaches Drama Series|Outstanding New Approaches Drama Series]] in 2015.<ref name="Variety Emmy 42 Nom">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/general-hospital-ellen-degeneres-young-and-the-restless-daytime-emmy-nominations-1201463476/ |title=''General Hospital'', ''Ellen DeGeneres'', CBS Lead Daytime Emmy Nominations |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |first=Cynthia |last=Littleton |date=March 31, 2015 |accessdate=September 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name="Backstage Emmy 42 Nom">{{cite web |url=http://www.backstage.com/news/general-hospital-leads-42nd-annual-daytime-emmy-nominations/ |title=''General Hospital'' Leads 42nd Annual Daytime Emmy Nominations |work=[[Backstage (magazine)|Backstage]] |first=Briana |last=Rodriguez |date=March 31, 2015 |accessdate=September 17, 2015}}</ref>
===Music=== Byrne is also a singer. She contributed a Christmas medley to the 1994 [[RCA|RCA release]], ''A Soap Opera Christmas.'' She released her self-titled album ''Martha Byrne'' in 1996.
She has also released a second album, ''Woman Thing Music''. Byrne again was the subject of controversy, as the sponsor of the second album was [[Philip Morris USA|Philip Morris]]. The CD could only be purchased in conjunction with the purchase of cigarettes, or at one of the "Woman Music Thing" concerts that Philip Morris sponsored. Byrne eventually withdrew endorsement from the music label, as she did not want to be associated with a product that could encourage underage smoking.
In 2006 Byrne released a third album, ''The Other Side''.
==Awards and recognition== Byrne is a ten-time [[Daytime Emmy Award]]-nominee as actress and producer, winning [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Younger Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Younger Actress]] in 1987, [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actress]] in 2001, and Outstanding Performer in a New Approaches Drama Series in 2015.
==Personal life== Byrne married Michael McMahon, a former undercover officer in the [[New York City Police Department]], on November 12, 1994.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C01EFDA1530F934A15752C1A962958260| title=Vows; Martha Byrne and Michael McMahon|work=[[The New York Times]]|date= November 27, 1994|first=Lois|last=Smith-Brady}}</ref> She grew up in [[Waldwick, New Jersey]]<ref>Rohan, Virginia. [http://www.northjersey.com/arts_entertainment/117452163_In_Paramus__a_showbiz_boot_camp.html?page=all "In Paramus, a showbiz boot camp"], ''[[The Record (Bergen County)]]'', March 5, 2011. Accessed December 20, 2013. "It was a different world in 1977, when a 9-year-old from Waldwick named Martha Byrne embarked on a big adventure in New York City. One of 700 hopefuls who went to an open call for the Broadway musical "Annie," Byrne landed the part of an orphan — and went on to a successful showbiz career."</ref> and lives in nearby [[Ridgewood, New Jersey|Ridgewood]].<ref>Staff. [http://www.bergen.com/Empires_Got_Talent_Bergen_County_native_Martha_Byrne_holds_Empire_star-studded_event.html "'Empire’s Got Talent': Bergen native Martha Byrne holds one night only event"], Bergen.com, November 8, 2011. Accessed December 20, 2013. "Waldwick native and Ridgewood resident Martha Byrne held an 'Empire’s Got Talent' event last night in New York City."</ref>
Their first child, Michael Terrence McMahon, was born on May 29, 1998. An episode of the [[The Learning Channel|TLC]] series ''[[A Baby Story]]'' chronicled her second pregnancy and the birth of her son, Maxwell Vincent McMahon, on September 3, 2002. Their third child and first daughter, Annmarie, was born June 12, 2006.
