'''National Ethiopian Art Theatre, Inc.,''' was an [[United States|American]] thespian company devoted to training, showcasing, and employing black American actors during the [[Harlem Renaissance]]. The company was founded by Mrs. [[Anne Wolte]]r on March 17, 1924, in [[New York City]]. The Ethiopian Art Theatre School was its educational arm.<ref>[http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2011/New%20York%20NY%20Age/New%20York%20NY%20Age%201924-1926%20%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Age%201924-1926%20%20Grayscale%20-%200089.pdf ''National Ethiopian Art Theatre School Opened in New York City March 17'', The New York Age, pps. 1 & 5, April 5, 1924, front page] [http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2011/New%20York%20NY%20Age/New%20York%20NY%20Age%201924-1926%20%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Age%201924-1926%20%20Grayscale%20-%200094.pdf page 5]</ref>
== Initial personnel == '''Corps of instructors''' * [[Philip Loeb]], director of the dramatic art department * Albert W. Noll, director of music * [[Henry Creamer]], director of dancing * George Bamman, science & technical director
